3. echanisms of eurodegeneration in 
 ccording to the beta-amyloid hypothesis, the accumulation and aggregation of beta-amyloid into toxic soluble oligomers is the first step leading to neuronal degeneration in  [18]. pecifically, an important early molecular step is the lost of synapses, which correlates highly with the initial memory impairment observed in  [19, 20]. ntensive research over the last two decades has examined potential pathways activated by beta-amyloid aggregates that lead to synaptic dysfunction,  formation, and eventual cell death.  igure 2 summarizes some of the major findings on beta-amyloid-induced toxicity that begin with either beta-amyloid activation of apoptotic pathways or promotion of oxidative stress. ith regards to apoptosis, since the early nineties, studies have supported a general role for apoptosis in  [21β€“23]. n addition, the activation of caspases, including caspase 3, 6, 8, and 9, has been documented in the  brain [24β€“30]. n turn, evidence suggests that once activated, caspases may cleave critical cellular proteins in  including , actin, fodrin, glial acidic fibrillary protein, beclin-1, and tau [28, 31β€“35]. mportantly, several studies have suggested that caspase activation and cleavage of tau may precede and contribute to the formation of s [31, 32, 36]. 
 n interlinking step between beta-amyloid and s could be the promotion of oxidative stress. xidative stress either through lipid peroxidation or mitochondrial disruption is an early feature found in  [37β€“39]. n addition, oxidative stress may contribute to the activation of apoptosis through both the extrinsic and intrinsic pathway [40, 41]. inally, tau phosphorylation is upregulated by oxidative stress [42] and tau filaments are modified by products of oxidative stress [43β€“45]. xidative stress also activates several kinases that have been implicated in the hyperphosphorylation of tau including glycogen synthase kinase-3 (3), un--terminal kinase (), and mitogen-activated protein kinases (s) [46, 47].3. Mechanisms of Neurodegeneration in AD
 According to the beta-amyloid hypothesis, the accumulation and aggregation of beta-amyloid into toxic soluble oligomers is the first step leading to neuronal degeneration in AD [18]. Specifically, an important early molecular step is the lost of synapses, which correlates highly with the initial memory impairment observed in AD [19, 20]. Intensive research over the last two decades has examined potential pathways activated by beta-amyloid aggregates that lead to synaptic dysfunction, NFT formation, and eventual cell death.  Figure 2 summarizes some of the major findings on beta-amyloid-induced toxicity that begin with either beta-amyloid activation of apoptotic pathways or promotion of oxidative stress. With regards to apoptosis, since the early nineties, studies have supported a general role for apoptosis in AD [21β€“23]. In addition, the activation of caspases, including caspase 3, 6, 8, and 9, has been documented in the AD brain [24β€“30]. In turn, evidence suggests that once activated, caspases may cleave critical cellular proteins in AD including APP, actin, fodrin, glial acidic fibrillary protein, beclin-1, and tau [28, 31β€“35]. Importantly, several studies have suggested that caspase activation and cleavage of tau may precede and contribute to the formation of NFTs [31, 32, 36]. 
 An interlinking step between beta-amyloid and NFTs could be the promotion of oxidative stress. Oxidative stress either through lipid peroxidation or mitochondrial disruption is an early feature found in AD [37β€“39]. In addition, oxidative stress may contribute to the activation of apoptosis through both the extrinsic and intrinsic pathway [40, 41]. Finally, tau phosphorylation is upregulated by oxidative stress [42] and tau filaments are modified by products of oxidative stress [43β€“45]. Oxidative stress also activates several kinases that have been implicated in the hyperphosphorylation of tau including glycogen synthase kinase-3 (GSK3), Jun-N-terminal kinase (JNK), and mitogen-activated protein kinases (MAPKs) [46, 47].
