4. nflammation in 
rain inflammation is a pathological hallmark of  [48, 49]. n this regard, numerous studies have supported a definitive role for inflammation in , with a key feature being the presence of activated microglia [50β€“52] and reactive astrocytes found within senile plaques [53β€“55]. pidemiological studies have also pointed to inflammation as central to , indicating that the long-term use of anti-inflammatory drugs is linked with reduced risk of developing the disease [56]. icroglia are key players in mediating immune responses in the  functioning as the resident macrophages of the  and as such contribute to a healthy  by attacking and removing potential pathogens and cell debris and by secreting tissue rebuilding factors [57]. 
 nterestingly, the link between the activation of microglia and inflammation may be beta-amyloid. hus, beta-amyloid is a potent inducer of microglia activation [52, 58β€“60], and one important role of microglia is to clear beta-amyloid deposits out of the  brain (for recent review, see [61]). 
ne potential caveat with inflammation is determining cause and effect. oes  cause inflammation? does the dysregulation of immune system pathways trigger the disease process? lternatively, although chronic inflammation may be a driving force in disease pathogenesis, it also may serve as a beneficial response at least early on during the course of . inally, it is possible that inflammation could simply be a byproduct of the disease process and may not effectively alter its course.  recent discovery has now addressed this issue and has unequivocally put inflammation in general and specifically the microglial response center stage.4. Inflammation in AD
Brain inflammation is a pathological hallmark of AD [48, 49]. In this regard, numerous studies have supported a definitive role for inflammation in AD, with a key feature being the presence of activated microglia [50β€“52] and reactive astrocytes found within senile plaques [53β€“55]. Epidemiological studies have also pointed to inflammation as central to AD, indicating that the long-term use of anti-inflammatory drugs is linked with reduced risk of developing the disease [56]. Microglia are key players in mediating immune responses in the CNS functioning as the resident macrophages of the CNS and as such contribute to a healthy CNS by attacking and removing potential pathogens and cell debris and by secreting tissue rebuilding factors [57]. 
 Interestingly, the link between the activation of microglia and inflammation may be beta-amyloid. Thus, beta-amyloid is a potent inducer of microglia activation [52, 58β€“60], and one important role of microglia is to clear beta-amyloid deposits out of the AD brain (for recent review, see [61]). 
One potential caveat with inflammation is determining cause and effect. Does AD cause inflammation? does the dysregulation of immune system pathways trigger the disease process? Alternatively, although chronic inflammation may be a driving force in disease pathogenesis, it also may serve as a beneficial response at least early on during the course of AD. Finally, it is possible that inflammation could simply be a byproduct of the disease process and may not effectively alter its course. A recent discovery has now addressed this issue and has unequivocally put inflammation in general and specifically the microglial response center stage.
